question: Does JMJD6 slow or inhibit hydroxylation of the C-terminal lysine of p53 (Lys382)? Answer with Yes or No.

content.source_1: We demonstrated that JMJD6 acts as an Î±-ketoglutarate- and Fe(II)-dependent lysyl hydroxylase to catalyze p53 hydroxylation.
content.source_2: While p53 is hydroxylated in vivo, kinetic profiling showed that its C-terminal lysine 382 accumulates hydroxylation more slowly when JMJD6 is present, indicating that JMJD6 restrains the modification rate.
content.source_3: Loss of JMJD6 activity led to diminished hydroxylation at the p53 C-terminus and reduced p53 target gene induction, consistent with JMJD6 functioning as a positive catalyst of lysine hydroxylation rather than an inhibitor.
